english:
  title: Viewing Lake Tower
  author: Cho Kan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The landscape of this tower melts the heart completely—
    Even the Eight Chants and Twin Streams cannot compare.
    Banners and carriages mingle on paths of woodcutters and shepherds,
    While zither melodies drift down to the homes of clerks and common folk.
    The eaves that tower into emptiness make the body bristle with awe,
    The high railings overlooking water dazzle the eyes with vertigo.
    Is this not the Guanghan Palace carved by a jade axe?
    Floating thus, I seem to arrive on celestial boats with immortals.
  footnotes:
    - The Eight Chants and Twin Streams (八咏・雙溪) refer to celebrated scenic locations in Chinese literature, establishing a comparison between this Korean tower and famous Chinese landscapes.
    - The Guanghan Palace (廣寒殿) is the palace of the Moon Goddess in Chinese mythology, suggesting the tower reaches toward the heavens.
    - The celestial boats (仙槎) alludes to the mythical boat that travels to heaven, conveying a sense of transcendence through experiencing this earthly beauty.
